  "updated_summary": "The aftermath of a supernova explosion is depicted as a bright, explosive starburst rapidly expands into a glowing blue nebula, with a male voice explaining that prior study of SN 1987A, a luminous blue supergiant, facilitated the combination of theories and observations regarding supernova prerequisites and aftermath. SN 1987A is noted as the last supernova visible from Earth with the unaided eye, emphasized by visuals of the galactic plane, a starburst, a spiral galaxy, and a pulsating red supernova remnant ring. The narrative shifts to the historical difficulty of finding and classifying supernovae, which relied on amateur astronomers sifting through photographs, contrasting with modern automated systems and improved surveying technologies that now discover hundreds of extragalactic supernovae annually. Supernovae are classified into Type I (no hydrogen) and Type II (shows hydrogen) based on spectroscopic measurements of elemental prevalence, a system introduced by Fritz Zwicky and Rudolph Minkowski in the 1940s, who initially classified ultrabright extragalactic supernovae due to a lack of data from within our own galaxy. Type I supernovae are described as more luminous and rare than Type II, which are classic massive star collapses. The process of stellar fusion is detailed, explaining that only stars more than eight times the mass of the sun can explode, fusing hydrogen into helium, then helium into carbon, and progressively heavier elements like oxygen, neon, magnesium, silicon, sulfur, calcium, and argon, until iron is formed, marking the end of energy generation. Fusion within the star's core previously produced energy, but nuclear reactions beyond iron require energy input, causing the star's layers to collapse suddenly under gravity at speeds up to 23% the speed of light. These collapsing layers form a ball of crushed subatomic particles, with free-roaming electrons exerting a force that pushes back against the collapse, preventing further crushing."
